The '''female epic''' is a concept in [[literary criticism]] that seeks to expand generic boundaries by identifying ways in which women authors have adapted the masculine epic tradition to express their own heroic visions.
Historically, [[Epic poetry|epic]] literature has been considered an exclusively male domain, to the extent that "epic and masculinity appear to be almost coterminous." <ref name="appanglo1">{{cite book | last = Schweizer | first = Bernard | title = Approaches to the Anglo and American Female Epic, 1621-1982 | publisher = Ashgate | location = Aldershot | year = 2006 | isbn = 0-7546-5486-9 |page =1}}</ref> From [[Homer]]'s [[Iliad]] to [[John Milton|Milton]]'s ''[[Paradise Lost]]'', the epic canon has been defined by works authored by men, and the characteristic subject matter and diction of the epic have carried connotations of masculinity. Recently, however, [[feminist]] literary critics have identified a number of texts written by women which, they argue, deserve to be considered epics, as they have many of the required qualities: emphasis on [[hero]]ism, [[Nation-building|nation building]], religious authority, a strong [[quest]] motif, and significant length.<ref>{{cite book | last = Schweizer | first = Bernard | title = Rebecca West: Heroism, Rebellion, and the Female Epic | publisher = Greenwood Press | location = Westport | year = 2002 | isbn = 0-313-32360-7 | page = 3}}</ref> Because these texts post-date Milton's ''Paradise Lost'' &ndash; conventionally considered to be the last authentic epic in the Western tradition &ndash;<ref>{{cite book | last = Fowler | first = Alastair | title =Kinds of Literature: An Introduction to the Theory of Genres and Modes| page = 167 | publisher=Harvard University Press | year=1985 }}</ref> they are by default "modern epics". However, argue these critics, this is by no means a contradiction. The epic remains an authentic and vital literary genre, and one to which women have made valuable contributions.<ref>Schweizer (2006), p. 6</ref>
The breadth of these studies is indicated by the essays in [[Bernard Schweizer]]'s ''Approaches to the Anglo and American Female Epic, 1621-1982'' (2006), which features studies of, among others, [[Lady Mary Wroth]]’s ''The Countesse of Montgomeries Urania'', [[Mary Tighe]]’s ''Psyche'', [[Elizabeth Barrett Browning]]’s ''[[Aurora Leigh]]'', [[Sharon Doubiago]]’s ''Hard Country'', and [[Rebecca West]]’s ''[[Black Lamb and Grey Falcon]]''.
